<h1>Problem 699 - 2008 USAMO, P3 of 6</h1>
<h2 class='difficulty'>Difficulty: 9</h2>
<p>Let \(n\) be a positive integer. Denote by \(S_n\) the set of points \((x, y)\) with integer coordinates such that\[\left\lvert x\right\rvert + \left\lvert y + \frac{1}{2} \right\rvert < n.\] A path is a sequence of distinct points \((x_1 , y_1), \ldots, (x_\ell, y_\ell)\) in \(S_n\) such that, for \(i = 2, \ldots, \ell\), the distance between \((x_i , y_i)\) and \((x_{i-1} , y_{i-1} )\) is \(1.\) Prove that the points in \(S_n\) cannot be partitioned into fewer than \(n\) paths.</p>
